<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1713,1956]" pageId="4" pageNumber="210">
The advertisement call of 
<taxonomicName authority="Braun and Braun 1979" box="[458,832,1713,1739]" class="Amphibia" family="Bufonidae" genus="Melanophryniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="4" pageNumber="210" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cambaraensis">
<emphasis box="[458,832,1713,1739]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="210">Melanophryniscus cambaraensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from FLONA SFP has an average duration of 18.8 seconds (SD = 6.51) and it is composed of segments A and B (
<figureCitation box="[870,966,1749,1775]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,974,998]" captionTargetBox="[418,1168,187,946]" captionTargetId="figure-25@5.[416,1172,181,950]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Oscillogram and spectrogram of Melanophryniscus cambaraensis call from FLONA SFP (A - FZ 9093) and a close view of the call (B); and a close view of the call of M. macrogranulosus from Garapiá (C – FZ9102) and from Morro da Gruta (D – FZ 9113). In each figure we show call part A (single pulses) and B (pulsed trill) of the call." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4315659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4315659/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="210">Figure 3</figureCitation>
A–B). Part A is composed of 3–11 single modulated notes, each one composed of one pulse (of 0.02 seconds each), separated by long time intervals of 0.38 seconds (SD = 0.052). Call part B is an extremely long train of unmodulated pulses emitted at a rate of 35.8 pulses per second (SD = 3.1), with short time intervals (Mean = 0.02; SD = 0.002), and lasting from 9–32.2 seconds (Mean = 16.6; SD = 6.8) (
<tableCitation box="[362,445,1893,1919]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,512,536]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Call characteristics of Melanophryniscus cambaraensis and M. macrogranulosus of the three sample sites. Values in the table are average ± standard deviation (range). ncalls = nº of calls, nind = nº of male individuals." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF6A6658FFAFFFC7FF2B0A41283EFDF7" pageId="4" pageNumber="210" tableUuid="DF6A6658FFAFFFC7FF2B0A41283EFDF7">Table 1</tableCitation>
). Peak frequency of both parts is quite similar being on average 2.2 kHz in part A (SD = 0.16) and 2.2 kHz in part B (SD = 0.17) (
<tableCitation box="[612,696,1929,1955]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,512,536]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Call characteristics of Melanophryniscus cambaraensis and M. macrogranulosus of the three sample sites. Values in the table are average ± standard deviation (range). ncalls = nº of calls, nind = nº of male individuals." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF6A6658FFAFFFC7FF2B0A41283EFDF7" pageId="4" pageNumber="210" tableUuid="DF6A6658FFAFFFC7FF2B0A41283EFDF7">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
